1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:02,300
When you're writing Python, you might want to make

2

00:00:02,300  -->  00:00:05,940
references in text to what certain parts mean or do.

3

00:00:05,940  -->  00:00:08,440
Especially as you work on Teams and with

4

00:00:08,440  -->  00:00:11,880
other engineers who wrote code for various parts of a project,

5

00:00:11,880  -->  00:00:15,840
certain actions or methods might be unfamiliar to you and others.

6

00:00:15,840  -->  00:00:21,620
Fortunately for us, Python has a very handy way to let us write text in our code.

7

00:00:21,620  -->  00:00:23,680
The best part of comments,

8

00:00:23,680  -->  00:00:28,300
besides letting us provide human readable documentation in our machine code,

9

00:00:28,300  -->  00:00:32,120
is that comments are ignored when Python actually runs.

10

00:00:32,120  -->  00:00:37,245
Meaning the comments will have no impact on the execution of the functions themselves.

11

00:00:37,245  -->  00:00:41,700
If we wanted to add comments to our greater function from earlier,

12

00:00:41,700  -->  00:00:46,060
we'll use the pound hashtag sign to then

13

00:00:46,060  -->  00:00:51,600
write out into the function some plain text references, like this.

14

00:00:51,600  -->  00:00:54,080
We can explain what the function does,

15

00:00:54,080  -->  00:00:58,020
for example, function to greet a friend.

16

00:00:58,020  -->  00:01:00,500
Then we could help add some clarity around

17

00:01:00,500  -->  00:01:03,680
the if statement and let other developers know,

18

00:01:03,680  -->  00:01:06,800
if a name is provided, then run this.

19

00:01:06,800  -->  00:01:10,200
We could then also define the L statement and say,

20

00:01:10,200  -->  00:01:15,265
if a name is not provided, do this instead.

21

00:01:15,265  -->  00:01:19,220
Then we can add some clarity around the execution of the function.

22

00:01:19,220  -->  00:01:21,450
Pass in the name,

23

00:01:21,450  -->  00:01:24,010
getting the function like this.

24

00:01:24,010  -->  00:01:27,490
Now, let's remove these comments for a moment.

25

00:01:27,490  -->  00:01:33,990
We can see how this makes our code so much more understandable when we have comments,

26

00:01:33,990  -->  00:01:37,025
especially if you didn't write this code out yourself.

27

00:01:37,025  -->  00:01:41,465
Without these comments, our code is much less understandable.

28

00:01:41,465  -->  00:01:46,550
We probably would need to go and review this code to really understand it.

29

00:01:46,550  -->  00:01:51,930
Sometimes you might want to write more text than just what can fit on a single line.

30

00:01:51,930  -->  00:01:57,030
For this, we can use either three quotation marks

31

00:01:57,030  -->  00:02:02,970
or three large quotation mark blocks to create a block comment, like this.

32

00:02:02,970  -->  00:02:06,075
We can define it with 1, 2, 3.

33

00:02:06,075  -->  00:02:10,440
One, two, three, and we could write a note like this,

34

00:02:10,440  -->  00:02:14,640
and we could help explain the arguments that would be

35

00:02:14,640  -->  00:02:19,040
expected for this function to run such as the name which is a string,

36

00:02:19,040  -->  00:02:21,040
or we would expect it to be a string.

37

00:02:21,040  -->  00:02:23,150
That's the name.

38

00:02:23,200  -->  00:02:28,745
Great. Then we could help define what is returned to the function.

39

00:02:28,745  -->  00:02:31,020
What's returned is a print statement.

40

00:02:31,020  -->  00:02:33,510
But it does not have any return statements.

41

00:02:33,510  -->  00:02:36,780
It just prints hello name or hello world.

42

00:02:36,780  -->  00:02:38,600
Also, as you'll see here,

43

00:02:38,600  -->  00:02:43,385
we could also do 1,2,3 and 1,2,3.

44

00:02:43,385  -->  00:02:45,380
If we hold out shift and enter,

45

00:02:45,380  -->  00:02:48,640
we'll see that our function runs and ignores

46

00:02:48,640  -->  00:02:53,540
the note here that we have as a comment block.

47

00:02:53,540  -->  00:02:56,800
We can write these comments and they won't be included in our execution.

48

00:02:56,800  -->  00:02:58,320
As we mentioned before,

49

00:02:58,320  -->  00:03:02,140
we can also do the double quotes and do three of those,

50

00:03:02,140  -->  00:03:03,820
and that will also execute.

51

00:03:03,820  -->  00:03:08,440
The same. The multiple lines of code in between here under

52

00:03:08,440  -->  00:03:13,760
the function definition is a specific type of multi line comment called a doc string,

53

00:03:13,760  -->  00:03:17,240
and this is used to describe the purpose of a function,

54

00:03:17,240  -->  00:03:22,060
method, class, or module right after its initialization,

55

00:03:22,060  -->  00:03:25,860
definition line, and follow a similar style to this,

56

00:03:25,860  -->  00:03:27,700
explaining what the function does,

57

00:03:27,700  -->  00:03:32,190
describing the arguments, and also what is returned from that function.

58

00:03:32,190  -->  00:03:36,420
Between the first function which does not have any comments and

59

00:03:36,420  -->  00:03:40,900
the second function which does have comments,

60

00:03:40,900  -->  00:03:42,500
which one do you like more?

61

00:03:42,500  -->  00:03:48,820
Which one do you feel is the most helpful for you as an engineer?

62

00:03:48,820  -->  00:03:53,200
This is the power of comments and explaining

63

00:03:53,200  -->  00:03:57,980
how code works and why it was written in the way that it was.

64

00:03:57,980  -->  00:03:59,780
You might be thinking, Well,

65

00:03:59,780  -->  00:04:01,500
when would I use comments?

66

00:04:01,500  -->  00:04:03,480
The answer is everywhere.

67

00:04:03,480  -->  00:04:07,300
Think of comments as your instructions that can help you or

68

00:04:07,300  -->  00:04:11,580
future engineers understand what is happening in the code and why.

69

00:04:11,580  -->  00:04:14,100
Now that we have some of the basics down,

70

00:04:14,100  -->  00:04:16,880
it's time to start taking a look at storing information,

71

00:04:16,880  -->  00:04:21,300
using variables, and the data types for those variables.
